WEBVTT

00:00.047 --> 00:02.140
ALEX: <i>Things with the company
were really coming together,</i>

00:02.203 --> 00:03.703
<i>but we were still missing a name.</i>

00:03.789 --> 00:06.937
Story Space... Story Place...

00:07.008 --> 00:09.571
Story... Amos?

00:09.628 --> 00:10.594
♪

00:10.619 --> 00:11.562
Apple!

00:11.587 --> 00:13.053
Oh, no, that's already a thing.

00:13.121 --> 00:14.187
♪

00:14.256 --> 00:15.755
Talk of the Town, Talk of the Night,

00:15.858 --> 00:17.190
Talk of the Truck, Taco Truck.

00:17.259 --> 00:19.893
Beets! Oh, damn you, Dr. Dre.

00:19.962 --> 00:22.128
Pod, Pod People, The Podsters.

00:22.231 --> 00:23.363
Fire.

00:23.398 --> 00:25.999
Ooh, I like that, like stories
around the campfire.

00:26.101 --> 00:28.168
No, like the bacon's on fire.

00:28.270 --> 00:30.837
<i>I was even working on it in my sleep.</i>

00:30.906 --> 00:33.540
Signal... Signal Media...

00:33.609 --> 00:36.710
Today's guest is Alex Schuman,

00:36.812 --> 00:39.412
the CEO of Signal Media.

00:39.481 --> 00:41.314
[Laughs] Oh.

00:41.383 --> 00:44.684
Thanks, Oprah, but I'm a married man...

00:44.753 --> 00:45.952
and what about Stedman?

00:46.054 --> 00:48.054
[Grunts]

00:48.156 --> 00:51.358
[Snores]

00:51.426 --> 00:52.859
I've got it!

00:52.961 --> 00:55.462
Guys, I've got the name!

00:55.531 --> 00:57.964
I've got it. I got the name.

00:58.033 --> 00:59.432
Prepare to be wowed.

00:59.564 --> 01:00.867
No, don't shake your head.

01:00.936 --> 01:02.435
You haven't even heard it yet.

01:02.538 --> 01:04.604
- It is...
- I'd like to be wowed.

01:05.607 --> 01:09.175
Honey, you didn't tell me
that your mother was visiting.

01:09.278 --> 01:11.378
What a fun surprise.

01:11.480 --> 01:14.514
<font color="#0080ff">Synced & corrected by</font> kinglouisxx
<font color="#0080ff">www.</font>addic7ed<font color="#0080ff">.com</font>

01:16.518 --> 01:17.617
What's your mother doing here?

01:17.719 --> 01:19.920
Sometimes moms just pop in unannounced.

01:20.022 --> 01:21.191
Who pops in from Dallas?

01:21.277 --> 01:23.523
And maybe she heard about you
starting your company

01:23.625 --> 01:25.692
and decided to come in
and provide the kids

01:25.794 --> 01:27.661
with some stability
during this turbulent time.

01:27.763 --> 01:29.362
Well, if she's here, I hope she's ready

01:29.464 --> 01:31.698
for some fun in the city, extra spicy,

01:31.800 --> 01:33.633
Indian-style, the full Schuman.

01:33.735 --> 01:34.668
No, no. No full Schuman.

01:34.770 --> 01:37.037
Please, babe, I really don't want you

01:37.139 --> 01:39.439
to do that thing where you try
overcompensating with her.

01:39.541 --> 01:41.374
I bet your mother would love
my overcompensating

01:41.476 --> 01:43.543
if I was that Bengali doctor
you used to date,

01:43.645 --> 01:46.212
that stupid, perfect Dr. Sandeep.

01:46.315 --> 01:48.048
Yeah, well, I didn't want
to marry a tall,

01:48.150 --> 01:49.382
handsome, successful doctor.

01:49.484 --> 01:51.384
I wanted to marry <i> you.</i>

01:52.487 --> 01:55.522
Okay, fine. No overcompensating.

01:55.624 --> 01:57.390
Maybe just some regular compensating

01:57.492 --> 01:59.693
with just a hint of under-compensating.

01:59.795 --> 02:00.961
Thank you.

02:01.063 --> 02:02.495
- [Cellphone plays Indian music]
- And to prove it to you,

02:02.598 --> 02:04.164
I'll be ignoring
that Google alert I just set

02:04.266 --> 02:05.999
for any and all Indian-themed events

02:06.101 --> 02:07.968
happening in the greater New York area.

02:08.070 --> 02:09.235
♪

02:09.338 --> 02:10.336
Joya!

02:10.439 --> 02:12.305
It really is good to see you.

02:12.407 --> 02:13.640
Good to see you, too,

02:13.742 --> 02:15.375
although I would have been fine
seeing a little less of you.

02:15.477 --> 02:17.344
Yes. Sorry for my lack of clothes.

02:17.446 --> 02:20.513
Or as you might say,
"Sorry, I forgot my sari."

02:20.616 --> 02:21.548
Oh, my God.

02:21.650 --> 02:22.649
Rooni, did I tell you

02:22.751 --> 02:24.417
that I recently became Facebook friends

02:24.519 --> 02:26.353
with your old friend Dr. Sandeep?

02:26.455 --> 02:29.648
And he posted the cutest video
of his gorgeous family.

02:29.718 --> 02:31.491
Why are they covered in colors?

02:31.593 --> 02:34.327
They are observing
the Hindu holiday of Holi.

02:34.429 --> 02:36.696
Your mother used to love Holi as a girl.

02:36.798 --> 02:38.698
I guess they decided
not to continue that tradition

02:38.800 --> 02:41.001
with the two of you... for some reason.

02:41.103 --> 02:44.004
Oh, Mom, isn't it a little early
for this much judgment?

02:44.106 --> 02:46.539
So, Alex, I hear that you decided

02:46.642 --> 02:48.208
to jeopardize your children's future

02:48.310 --> 02:50.510
by quitting your radio DJ job
to start a new company.

02:50.612 --> 02:53.213
I guess that means it's <i>not</i> too early.
The company's going great.

02:53.315 --> 02:54.414
Thank you for asking.

02:54.516 --> 02:56.616
We launch our first podcast
in a few weeks.

02:56.718 --> 02:58.685
[Snaps fingers] Come to think of it,

02:58.787 --> 03:01.621
since the family is
such a big part of the series,

03:01.723 --> 03:03.657
it would be wonderful to get you on tape

03:03.759 --> 03:05.358
to hear some of your thoughts
on everything.

03:05.460 --> 03:09.329
[Speaking Hindi] _

03:10.332 --> 03:11.698
She said, "Maybe later."

03:11.800 --> 03:13.266
Okay. That's one's gonna be,
"Maybe later."

03:13.368 --> 03:14.467
Awesome.

03:14.569 --> 03:17.470
So, what is this company called?

03:17.572 --> 03:20.674
The name has actually been
a little hard to come by.

03:20.776 --> 03:22.942
But this morning,
while washing my undercarriage,

03:23.045 --> 03:23.943
I think I found it.

03:24.046 --> 03:25.645
The name or your undercarriage?

03:25.747 --> 03:27.013
[Laughter]

03:27.115 --> 03:29.783
The name. Kids, drumroll.

03:31.086 --> 03:35.288
The Universal Radio Directive.

03:35.390 --> 03:37.123
♪

03:37.225 --> 03:40.060
It's so... long.

03:40.162 --> 03:41.227
It hurts my brain.

03:41.329 --> 03:42.595
The acronym is "turd."

03:42.698 --> 03:44.597
[Laughing] Dad's making a giant turd!

03:44.700 --> 03:46.700
No, no. I'm not gonna make a turd.

03:46.802 --> 03:48.668
It sounded better when I was soapy.

03:48.770 --> 03:50.270
You should have stayed a DJ.

03:50.372 --> 03:52.372
Everyone in New York needs DJs.

03:52.474 --> 03:54.407
There are weddings, bar mitzvahs...

03:54.509 --> 03:56.576
Mom, you know he wasn't
an actual DJ, right?

03:56.678 --> 03:57.777
I wasn't a DJ.

03:57.879 --> 04:00.480
...Quinceañeras, block parties,
proms, hootenannies.

04:00.582 --> 04:01.648
Magic shows.

04:01.750 --> 04:03.650
Raves.

04:03.752 --> 04:05.318
Kids, come on!

04:05.420 --> 04:07.887
Grandma Express leaves in five!

04:09.124 --> 04:11.157
Thanks again for handling drop-off, Mom.

04:11.259 --> 04:13.927
Hmm, anything to help launch
your husband's giant turd.

04:14.029 --> 04:16.161
Could you please just try

04:16.264 --> 04:18.164
to take it easy on Alex a bit?

04:18.266 --> 04:21.301
He gets so anxious
just trying to please you.

04:21.403 --> 04:23.636
You know who else I was tough on? You.

04:23.739 --> 04:25.138
And you turned out to be

04:25.240 --> 04:27.340
a very successful public defender.

04:27.442 --> 04:29.342
But, you know,
maybe I should have treated you

04:29.444 --> 04:31.244
like your cousin Debesh, huh?

04:31.346 --> 04:34.180
My sister coddled him,
treated him like a prince,

04:34.282 --> 04:36.850
and now he's a Prince... impersonator.

04:36.918 --> 04:38.618
- Okay, Mom, please.
- [Sighs]

04:38.687 --> 04:39.753
Fine.

04:39.821 --> 04:41.988
If it means that much to you,

04:42.057 --> 04:43.022
I'll be nice.

04:43.125 --> 04:44.924
- What's this?
- Alex likes to leave

04:44.993 --> 04:46.526
a little joke in their lunch every day.

04:46.595 --> 04:48.294
"How do you make a tissue dance?

04:48.363 --> 04:49.929
Put a little boogie in it."

04:50.899 --> 04:52.766
He doesn't make it easy.

04:52.868 --> 04:54.400
No, he really doesn't.

04:54.469 --> 04:55.568
Let me ask you something.

04:55.637 --> 04:57.337
What's the one thing
every company here has

04:57.405 --> 04:58.355
that we don't?

04:58.406 --> 04:59.572
- Mints.
- Diversity.

04:59.641 --> 05:00.940
A name.

05:01.009 --> 05:02.642
Oh, that was gonna be my next guess.

05:02.744 --> 05:04.377
Sure would be nice
to have those mints, though.

05:04.446 --> 05:05.979
Guys, we can't keep putting this off.

05:06.081 --> 05:07.847
No one is gonna take
this company seriously

05:07.916 --> 05:08.982
until we have a name.

05:09.084 --> 05:10.850
And to be honest,
it's a little embarrassing.

05:10.919 --> 05:13.920
I mean, even the Virtual Reality
Machine guys found a name.

05:14.022 --> 05:15.855
EDDIE: Ve Are VR?

05:15.924 --> 05:18.525
Sure, it's not great,
but you get who vey vare.

05:18.593 --> 05:20.860
Does this sudden motivation
have anything to do

05:20.929 --> 05:22.462
with your mother-in-law being in town?

05:22.531 --> 05:24.731
Ed, having a name
would give us legitimacy

05:24.833 --> 05:26.166
in the eyes of a lot of people.

05:26.234 --> 05:27.433
[Cellphone plays Indian music]

05:27.502 --> 05:28.701
Including my mother-in-law.

05:28.770 --> 05:29.669
[Cellphone clicks]

05:29.738 --> 05:31.871
"Interested in Indian threesomes?"

05:31.940 --> 05:33.573
It's probably for golf.

05:33.642 --> 05:36.476
Deirdre, what's the current
status of our name search?

05:36.545 --> 05:38.511
Well, currently, our status is nothing.

05:38.613 --> 05:41.147
But one of my roommates
works for a branding agency

05:41.216 --> 05:42.749
that specializes in naming.

05:42.818 --> 05:44.450
They name everything from businesses,

05:44.553 --> 05:46.252
to Ikea furniture, to new diseases.

05:46.354 --> 05:47.854
Flardstorp... That was them.

05:47.923 --> 05:49.725
I think that's the name
of my shelving unit.

05:49.803 --> 05:51.691
No. Actually, it's the hot new bird flu.

05:51.793 --> 05:53.293
- Should I set up a meeting?
- I don't know.

05:53.395 --> 05:56.196
Hiring some corporate,
soulless agency to name us...

05:56.264 --> 05:57.664
It goes against the very first thing

05:57.732 --> 06:00.500
I'm looking for in a name,
which is authenticity.

06:00.569 --> 06:02.468
I like it when a name has two meanings,

06:02.571 --> 06:03.937
like the movie "Face Off."

06:04.005 --> 06:05.939
Okay, this is good.

06:06.007 --> 06:07.740
You know, why don't we...
why don't we just make a list

06:07.843 --> 06:09.542
of everything we want in a name?
Deirdre.

06:09.611 --> 06:11.811
Okay, I like names that are
subtle and clean, you know,

06:11.880 --> 06:13.446
like one syllable, and remind people

06:13.515 --> 06:16.416
of a simpler time,
like "Cream" or "Yurt."

06:16.518 --> 06:18.151
Okay.

06:18.220 --> 06:19.586
I'm not sure about those specific names,

06:19.688 --> 06:20.820
but I like the thought.

06:20.889 --> 06:22.322
♪

06:22.390 --> 06:24.157
- Morning, Stanley.
- Morning, Ben.

06:24.259 --> 06:26.726
I think it's weird that you know
all the janitors' names.

06:26.828 --> 06:28.561
I think it's weird that you <i> don't.</i>

06:29.731 --> 06:31.598
You've got to be kidding me.

06:31.700 --> 06:34.868
Sven Chang has been killing it
with the ladies lately.

06:34.970 --> 06:36.669
Even Chloe!

06:36.738 --> 06:38.571
Yeah,<i> my</i> Chloe.

06:38.640 --> 06:40.540
I don't get it.
What's so great about him?

06:40.609 --> 06:43.343
I guess they think he's cool
because he's super diverse.

06:43.378 --> 06:46.145
The guy is Swedish,
Chinese,<i> and</i> Brazilian.

06:46.214 --> 06:47.547
We just had a Multicultural unit,

06:47.616 --> 06:50.316
and it was like a week-long
Sven Chang propaganda piece.

06:50.385 --> 06:51.751
Well, you're diverse.

06:51.853 --> 06:53.887
You're Indian and whatever dad is.

06:53.955 --> 06:55.321
New Jersian, I guess.

06:55.390 --> 06:56.656
But nobody knows that.

06:56.725 --> 06:58.191
My name is Ben Schuman!

06:58.293 --> 07:00.159
I sound like I'm an orthodontist
with an herb garden.

07:00.228 --> 07:02.862
Too bad you didn't get
this multiracial skin

07:02.964 --> 07:04.430
or a name like Soraya.

07:04.499 --> 07:06.266
I-I just wish there was a way

07:06.334 --> 07:08.001
to showcase my Indian side.

07:08.103 --> 07:10.236
Dude, Sven Chang just brought in these!

07:10.338 --> 07:11.871
Have some Swedish meatball dumplings.

07:11.940 --> 07:13.072
You gotta try them.

07:13.141 --> 07:17.210
Angelo, you just gave me a great idea.

07:17.279 --> 07:19.679
God, I love Sven Chang!

07:19.781 --> 07:20.847
ALEX: Okay.

07:20.916 --> 07:23.650
So, all we need is an authentic,
one-syllable name

07:23.718 --> 07:26.019
that reminds people of a bygone era,

07:26.087 --> 07:28.288
either includes
or definitely doesn't include

07:28.356 --> 07:29.822
the word "podcast,"

07:29.891 --> 07:32.525
is familiar but not <i> too</i> familiar,

07:32.627 --> 07:34.327
doesn't think it's better than you,

07:34.396 --> 07:38.264
and possibly has two meanings,
like the movie "Face Off."

07:38.333 --> 07:40.667
[Sighs] Naming stuff is hard.

07:40.735 --> 07:42.735
This is why I never buy plants.

07:42.837 --> 07:44.203
Yeah, and even if you like a name today,

07:44.272 --> 07:45.939
doesn't mean that you're gonna
like it tomorrow.

07:46.007 --> 07:49.309
When I was a kid, I named
my imaginary friend Fuzzybottom,

07:49.377 --> 07:52.045
and now I feel kind of silly
calling her that.

07:52.147 --> 07:54.447
Maybe we should just go with
Deirdre's name guys.

07:54.549 --> 07:56.716
I read online they came up with
"Hot Pockets."

07:56.818 --> 07:58.551
I mean, they're obviously talented.

07:58.653 --> 08:00.153
Come on, you guys. We can do this.

08:00.255 --> 08:01.321
This is our identity.

08:01.389 --> 08:03.823
It's gonna tell people who we are.

08:03.925 --> 08:05.124
So...

08:05.193 --> 08:07.493
Who are we?

08:07.595 --> 08:13.433
♪

08:13.535 --> 08:14.701
You know what?

08:14.803 --> 08:16.736
Maybe we should take
a little break, clear our heads.

08:18.179 --> 08:20.473
I got an idea.

08:20.575 --> 08:22.442
Surprising Alex with a pizza party

08:22.544 --> 08:23.710
was a great idea, Mom.

08:23.812 --> 08:25.144
Well, you said to be nice.

08:25.246 --> 08:27.447
Your auntie was the inspiration.

08:27.549 --> 08:30.116
She used to surprise
your cousin Debesh with snacks

08:30.218 --> 08:31.451
while he was pulling all-nighters

08:31.553 --> 08:33.686
recording his cover
of "Raspberry Beret."

08:33.788 --> 08:35.087
I know Dad likes pizzas,

08:35.190 --> 08:36.990
but I would have preferred samosas.

08:37.092 --> 08:38.957
We Bengalis have
a different name for samosas.

08:39.059 --> 08:40.326
We call them "singaras."

08:40.428 --> 08:42.328
[Elevator bell dings]

08:42.429 --> 08:44.464
That's awesome.

08:44.566 --> 08:47.300
Do you think you can show me
how to make them sometime?

08:47.402 --> 08:50.470
Like, enough to feed
a classroom-amount of people?

08:50.572 --> 08:51.804
Of course.

08:51.906 --> 08:53.940
These things are an important
part of your identity.

08:54.042 --> 08:56.442
♪

08:56.544 --> 08:59.412
So, is this some kind of a sweatshop?

08:59.514 --> 09:01.748
I know it's a little funky,

09:01.850 --> 09:03.916
but everyone here is working hard

09:04.019 --> 09:05.084
to pursue their dreams.

09:05.186 --> 09:06.919
And no one works harder than Alex.

09:07.022 --> 09:08.588
I actually think you'll be impressed

09:08.690 --> 09:09.789
when you see him in action.

09:09.891 --> 09:11.457
ALEX: I'm gonna land
on that little rock over there!

09:11.559 --> 09:12.525
MAN: Go for it.

09:12.627 --> 09:15.906
Oh, look at these cute little creatures!

09:15.984 --> 09:18.351
- Hit them with the fireball!
- Oh, I don't want to hurt them. Aah!

09:18.421 --> 09:20.466
- They're the bad guys! They're bad guys.
- They're attacking my legs!

09:20.568 --> 09:21.768
They're attacking me!

09:21.793 --> 09:22.769
- I'm sorry.
- I gotta get outta here!

09:22.871 --> 09:23.803
Just hold on.

09:23.905 --> 09:26.606
Aah! Aah!

09:26.708 --> 09:29.175
It <i> is</i> nice to see him in action.

09:30.120 --> 09:31.112
<i>I was so obsessed</i>

09:31.190 --> 09:32.925
<i>with how I'd embarrassed myself
in front of Joya</i>

09:33.007 --> 09:35.143
<i>that I couldn't even focus
on the name search.</i>

09:35.214 --> 09:36.279
Thrust.

09:36.382 --> 09:38.515
Grind.

09:38.584 --> 09:40.252
Hump.

09:40.315 --> 09:41.918
I used to have glutes like that.

09:42.432 --> 09:45.214
- Too much upkeep.
- Alex!

09:45.300 --> 09:47.621
Sorry, guys. I'm just... I'm in my head.

09:47.684 --> 09:49.238
Rooni was acting so weird this morning.

09:49.309 --> 09:50.842
Maybe Joya's finally getting to her.

09:50.944 --> 09:52.310
I'm pretty sure she was the one

09:52.412 --> 09:54.212
who locked you in that
broom closet at your wedding.

09:54.281 --> 09:55.447
Really?

09:55.515 --> 09:57.615
Whoever it was brought a hammer
and nails to my wedding.

09:57.684 --> 09:59.684
I just can't imagine
somebody not liking you.

09:59.786 --> 10:00.885
I mean, you're Alex.

10:00.954 --> 10:02.787
You're the reason people
wake up in the morning.

10:03.490 --> 10:04.923
Some people. Not me.

10:05.025 --> 10:06.191
Hey, if it makes you feel any better,

10:06.259 --> 10:07.792
Indian women aren't into me, either.

10:07.861 --> 10:11.029
Now, Pakistani women...
they can't get enough.

10:11.098 --> 10:12.597
Turns out, I am one of the many things

10:12.699 --> 10:13.965
those countries don't agree on.

10:14.067 --> 10:15.300
I just wish there was some way

10:15.368 --> 10:16.701
to change Joya's mind about me.

10:16.803 --> 10:18.036
Yeah, well, we could work on that

10:18.105 --> 10:19.270
or we could talk about a name.

10:19.372 --> 10:20.572
You're right. I'm sorry.

10:20.640 --> 10:22.107
- Let's focus.
- Okay.

10:22.175 --> 10:24.542
[Cellphone plays Indian music]

10:24.611 --> 10:26.978
I'll be right back.

10:27.080 --> 10:28.113
Dad, where are we going?

10:28.215 --> 10:29.581
It's a surprise, but don't worry.

10:29.649 --> 10:31.349
- You're gonna love it.
- You better not be taking me

10:31.451 --> 10:33.785
to put on a robot hat
and have gremlins eat my legs.

10:33.887 --> 10:35.186
Yesterday, I couldn't help but notice

10:35.255 --> 10:36.387
you were a little disappointed

10:36.490 --> 10:38.223
that our family
doesn't celebrate Holi...

10:38.291 --> 10:41.292
A holiday that signifies
fresh starts, forgiveness,

10:41.394 --> 10:43.261
repairing broken relationships.

10:43.330 --> 10:45.096
Are you taking us to a Holi?!

10:45.198 --> 10:46.931
Awesome, we're gonna get messy!

10:47.000 --> 10:48.500
Alex, that is very sweet!

10:48.568 --> 10:50.935
You know, I have some of
the most wonderful memories

10:51.037 --> 10:52.170
of Holi as a child.

10:52.272 --> 10:53.805
Well, prepare to have
some more wonderful memories

10:53.874 --> 10:55.140
of Holi as an adult!

10:55.208 --> 10:57.442
- <i>[Electronic music plays]</i>
- MAN: That's right, baby!

10:57.544 --> 10:59.544
[Cheering]

10:59.613 --> 11:01.613
This isn't Holi!

11:01.715 --> 11:03.648
I think I'm the only Indian person here.

11:03.717 --> 11:05.383
Guess I should've read
the website closer.

11:05.485 --> 11:06.818
This juice tastes funny.

11:06.887 --> 11:08.987
- I can't feel my face.
- Give me that!

11:09.055 --> 11:11.089
Look, Joya, I know this isn't probably

11:11.191 --> 11:12.657
the kind of Holi you're used to,

11:12.726 --> 11:14.425
but I think we can still have fun.

11:14.528 --> 11:15.894
Holi!

11:15.996 --> 11:17.362
♪

11:17.464 --> 11:20.064
You know what? It's not that fun.

11:20.167 --> 11:22.534
[Spitting]

11:23.937 --> 11:25.203
The important thing to remember

11:25.272 --> 11:26.938
is that this is one of those
freak things that happens,

11:27.040 --> 11:28.573
and it really isn't anyone's fault.

11:28.642 --> 11:30.241
Go dry off. I want to talk to your dad.

11:30.277 --> 11:32.811
Or you know what, stay here
and we'll all go in together.

11:33.547 --> 11:35.814
Stay strong, Dad.

11:35.882 --> 11:38.216
We'll see you on the other side.

11:41.354 --> 11:43.588
Ow! It's too pointy!
That's my nighttime zone!

11:43.657 --> 11:45.357
Why couldn't you just do what I asked?

11:45.436 --> 11:47.192
I tried. But you don't know
what it's like

11:47.260 --> 11:48.459
having to deal with your
mother's constant disapproval.

11:48.528 --> 11:50.161
You think I don't know what that's like?

11:50.263 --> 11:51.170
I'm just saying,

11:51.264 --> 11:52.664
I could use a little bit
more support with your mother.

11:53.400 --> 11:54.566
[Spits, coughs]

11:54.634 --> 11:56.401
You want to talk about support?

11:56.503 --> 11:57.869
Where's <i> my</i> support?

11:57.971 --> 12:00.171
While you're off chasing your dreams,

12:00.240 --> 12:02.941
I'm here struggling
to hold our lives together.

12:03.009 --> 12:05.176
You think I <i> wanted</i>
to ask my mom for help?

12:05.245 --> 12:06.544
Wait, you <i> asked</i> her to come?

12:06.646 --> 12:07.645
I needed help,

12:07.714 --> 12:09.747
and I knew if I asked you,
you'd freak out.

12:09.850 --> 12:11.216
I cannot believe you lied to me.

12:11.284 --> 12:13.184
We're supposed to be honest
with each other no matter what.

12:13.286 --> 12:14.986
- You want honesty?
- Yes.

12:15.088 --> 12:16.554
I'm scared.

12:16.656 --> 12:19.657
We have so much riding on this...

12:19.759 --> 12:22.694
our savings, this house, our careers...

12:22.796 --> 12:25.363
and you can't even name
your own company.

12:26.090 --> 12:29.258
I love that you're the guy
with these big dreams.

12:29.344 --> 12:30.376
But right now,

12:30.470 --> 12:32.971
I need you to be the guy
who can get things done.

12:33.073 --> 12:33.972
♪

12:34.074 --> 12:37.375
[Door opens, closes]

12:37.477 --> 12:38.643
[Coughs]

12:39.608 --> 12:40.709
<i>After what Rooni said,</i>

12:40.748 --> 12:42.256
<i>it was time
to call in the professionals.</i>

12:42.326 --> 12:44.373
Let me tell you a little bit
about what we do.

12:44.460 --> 12:45.559
We name things.

12:45.631 --> 12:47.164
- Mm.
- Let me tell you a little more.

12:47.266 --> 12:50.348
- We name the crap out of things.
- Mm!

12:50.426 --> 12:52.059
Well, that's great
because we need a name,

12:52.169 --> 12:53.301
and for whatever reason,

12:53.403 --> 12:55.149
it's been impossible for us
to come up with one.

12:55.231 --> 12:57.432
Impossible is our specialty!

12:57.509 --> 13:01.476
Mindr, Findr, Bindr, Windr... All us.

13:01.546 --> 13:02.921
Show them the dogs.

13:02.992 --> 13:06.656
Celebrity dogs... Named... them... all.

13:06.710 --> 13:08.377
- I told you these guys were very good.
- That's good.

13:08.479 --> 13:09.645
So, does that answer your question?

13:09.747 --> 13:11.013
I don't think we asked a question.

13:11.082 --> 13:12.481
No, we never got a chance
to ask questions.

13:12.550 --> 13:13.592
No, not out loud.

13:13.648 --> 13:15.882
Um, but, do you have a name for us?

13:15.951 --> 13:18.251
Uh, yeah, I'd say we have a name.

13:18.411 --> 13:20.087
♪

13:20.189 --> 13:22.055
Squiz Media.

13:22.124 --> 13:23.824
What's a Squiz?

13:23.892 --> 13:24.925
It isn't anything.

13:24.994 --> 13:26.433
You don't have to worry about people

13:26.495 --> 13:29.696
having any pre-existing
negative associations.

13:29.765 --> 13:33.233
So, how does Squiz relate
to our identity as a company?

13:33.302 --> 13:35.335
Nobody cares about that stuff, A-money.

13:35.404 --> 13:38.538
This has been focus-grouped
from Maine to Spain.

13:38.641 --> 13:40.340
Squiz is a sure thing.

13:40.409 --> 13:42.774
It's fun. It's sharp.

13:42.852 --> 13:43.977
[Whispering] It's now.

13:44.046 --> 13:45.445
[Whispering] Right now.

13:45.514 --> 13:46.680
So, what do you say?

13:46.782 --> 13:48.649
W-We do need a name ASAP,

13:48.717 --> 13:51.918
and y-you did test it
from Maine to Spain.

13:52.021 --> 13:54.254
Uh, okay. Uh...

13:54.356 --> 13:56.456
Let's go with Squiz.

13:56.525 --> 13:57.524
- Yeah.
- Whoo!

13:57.626 --> 13:58.925
We're in Squiz-ness.

13:58.994 --> 14:00.427
- Yay.
- DEIRDRE: Cool.

14:00.496 --> 14:04.531
You may know these as samosas,
but in the Bengal,

14:04.600 --> 14:08.502
where my family is from,
we call them singaras.

14:08.570 --> 14:10.804
I saved the biggest one for you, Chloe.

14:10.906 --> 14:12.005
This looks amazing.

14:12.107 --> 14:13.774
It's an old family recipe.

14:13.842 --> 14:16.276
Tradition is very important
in my culture.

14:18.243 --> 14:19.267
Ooh!

14:19.328 --> 14:20.741
Sorry, Sven.

14:20.774 --> 14:21.848
Must have miscounted.

14:21.950 --> 14:25.232
All right, everyone... [speaking Nepali]

14:25.302 --> 14:28.474
Or as my French great-grandfather

14:28.555 --> 14:32.424
on my dad's side
would say,<i> bon appetite!</i>

14:32.961 --> 14:35.962
♪

14:37.866 --> 14:42.436
[All coughing]

14:43.639 --> 14:44.705
GIRL: Too spicy!

14:44.807 --> 14:45.672
♪

14:46.896 --> 14:49.976
Oh, no. We went too authentic!

14:50.045 --> 14:51.344
Why?!

14:51.413 --> 14:52.546
My insides are on fire!

14:52.648 --> 14:55.010
My organs are staging a revolution!

14:55.088 --> 14:56.516
Don't worry, Chloe. The singaras here.

14:56.618 --> 14:58.218
Stay with me, stay with me.

14:58.287 --> 14:59.853
I hate you, Ben Schuman!

14:59.955 --> 15:02.889
I'm assuming you're finished?

15:02.958 --> 15:04.558
He has a juice box!

15:04.626 --> 15:06.393
WOMAN: Angelo, sit down!

15:06.495 --> 15:09.362
Everyone sit down!

15:09.431 --> 15:12.663
I've never been to war,
but it can't be worse

15:12.725 --> 15:14.735
than what happened
in that classroom today.

15:15.604 --> 15:18.338
The school paper is calling it
"The Singara Horra."

15:18.407 --> 15:21.282
Oh, Ben, I am so sorry.

15:21.329 --> 15:22.712
I guess I'm just not used to

15:22.774 --> 15:24.745
cooking for American children.

15:24.813 --> 15:25.912
I don't get it.

15:25.981 --> 15:28.749
Why is it so hard
to get girls to like me?

15:29.533 --> 15:30.550
You used to be a girl.

15:30.652 --> 15:33.420
- What did Grandpa do to get you?
- [Laughs]

15:33.522 --> 15:35.314
Your grandfather didn't <i> do</i> anything.

15:35.377 --> 15:37.494
It was an arranged marriage.

15:37.549 --> 15:39.781
My father talked to his father,
we met once,

15:39.843 --> 15:41.605
and then, that was it. We were married.

15:41.630 --> 15:42.796
That sounds so much easier.

15:42.865 --> 15:44.097
How can I get one of those?

15:44.166 --> 15:45.932
Arranged marriages aren't all great.

15:46.034 --> 15:47.734
It worked for me, but you're lucky

15:47.836 --> 15:50.570
to live someplace where you
get to choose your own partner.

15:50.672 --> 15:53.240
One reason why your grandfather
and I moved to this country

15:53.308 --> 15:55.842
was so that our children
could know that kind of freedom.

15:55.911 --> 15:57.277
So...

15:57.346 --> 16:01.148
you're not mad that Mom chose
to marry Dad over Dr. Sandeep?

16:01.250 --> 16:02.849
What? [Laughs] No.

16:02.918 --> 16:04.818
Why would you think that?

16:04.920 --> 16:06.613
Well, it's pretty obvious

16:06.660 --> 16:08.421
that you don't like my dad very much.

16:08.446 --> 16:09.466
♪

16:09.491 --> 16:12.325
Sweetheart, that is not true.

16:12.394 --> 16:14.995
Your father is a good man.

16:15.097 --> 16:17.130
We might not see eye-to-eye
on everything,

16:17.232 --> 16:19.800
but he takes good care of you

16:19.902 --> 16:23.003
and he makes your mother very happy.

16:23.071 --> 16:24.538
ALEX: Hey, Alex Schuman.

16:24.606 --> 16:27.808
Squiz Media, double handshake.

16:27.910 --> 16:29.142
[Sighs]

16:29.244 --> 16:30.510
[Sighs]

16:30.555 --> 16:31.588
I'm a Squizzer.

16:31.613 --> 16:33.180
Alex, can I interrupt...

16:33.282 --> 16:35.415
whatever it is that's going on here?

16:35.517 --> 16:38.318
Joya, I'm really not in the mood
to be insulted right now.

16:38.420 --> 16:39.486
Okay.

16:39.555 --> 16:42.644
Look, I know that I have
given you a hard time

16:42.691 --> 16:44.144
about starting this company.

16:44.235 --> 16:46.246
I also know, more than most,

16:46.293 --> 16:48.027
that it takes a lot of courage

16:48.090 --> 16:49.230
to leave what you know behind

16:49.277 --> 16:51.431
in order to give yourself
and your family a better life.

16:52.235 --> 16:53.334
Thank you.

16:54.627 --> 16:57.103
I gotta say, it's a lot harder
than I thought.

16:57.172 --> 16:59.606
I know Rooni told you she was worried,

16:59.708 --> 17:01.741
but I have to be honest.

17:02.281 --> 17:03.580
I'm worried, too.

17:03.642 --> 17:05.712
I have everything on the line.

17:07.015 --> 17:09.015
I'm going to tell you a story.

17:09.188 --> 17:12.182
So, get your giant microphone
out of your manny-pac.

17:12.268 --> 17:13.627
- It's going to be a good one.
- Really?

17:13.722 --> 17:15.622
That's great.
You know, the sound out here...

17:15.723 --> 17:16.890
The sound is fine.

17:19.428 --> 17:21.461
When I was a little girl in Calcutta,

17:21.530 --> 17:23.973
my grandfather treated me differently

17:24.035 --> 17:25.498
than he treated all of the sisters

17:25.567 --> 17:26.833
and the girl-cousins.

17:26.902 --> 17:28.869
He treated me, for some reason,

17:28.971 --> 17:30.203
like one of the boys.

17:30.272 --> 17:32.706
He would send me, all by myself,

17:32.774 --> 17:34.941
to the market to get potatoes

17:35.043 --> 17:37.377
or hilsa... the king of the fish...

17:37.446 --> 17:39.579
when I was no older than Soraya.

17:39.681 --> 17:41.848
That's so young.
You must have been terrified.

17:41.950 --> 17:44.417
I was. And I told my dadu.

17:44.519 --> 17:47.153
And he sat me down, and he said,

17:47.222 --> 17:50.657
"You don't even know
what you are afraid of.

17:50.759 --> 17:53.405
You must never fear <i> ajana,"</i>

17:53.467 --> 17:56.129
which in Bengali means "the unknown."

17:56.198 --> 17:58.965
"Because," he went on to say,

17:59.034 --> 18:02.936
<i>"ajana</i> is where
all the good things happen."

18:03.038 --> 18:06.339
I never forgot that.

18:06.408 --> 18:09.142
And even now,
every time that I'm afraid,

18:09.211 --> 18:11.478
I see that little 7-year-old girl

18:11.580 --> 18:13.280
throwing her shoulders back

18:13.382 --> 18:16.965
and marching into
that crowded market in Calcutta.

18:18.426 --> 18:19.505
So...

18:20.889 --> 18:24.358
throw your shoulders back, Alex Schuman.

18:26.194 --> 18:29.629
♪

